Introduction

In this notebook we aim to provide knowledge about performing advance Data analytics using R, from the dataset load to further Deep learning approaches passing trough all data transformations required in the process, even this techniques could be used for many tasks, the provided examples will be in the Natural Language Processing (NLP) field, first of all we are going to discuss the modules that we are using in the following sections:

  1. RTools: This package is required for building the following packages.

  2. tm: This package is used for applying VCorpus structures and the general Natural Language Processing (NLP) pipeline.

  3. SnowballC: THis library is used to apply the stemming proccess over words.

  4. h2o: This library is use to apply Deep Learning methods over the data.

  5. caret: This library is used to apply general Machine Learning methods. (be aware that you might need to install some of the following packages)

  • e1071: This library is used to provide support calculations for caret library.
  • kernlab: This library is needed for SVM model
  1. twitteR: This library is used to access Twitter platform and retrieve data. (be aware that you might need to install some of the following packages)
  • devtools: This library is used to provide functions to treat tweets data.
  1. quanteda: Quantitative analysis of textual data use R version > 3.5, contains NLP tools and very powerful with data features and very easy to use on CSV, TSv files https://quanteda.io/
  • data.table: Fast aggregation of large data and fast in ordered joins, and add/modify/delete of columns. https://cran.r-project.org/web/packages/data.table/index.html

  1. tidyverse: A package to read, plot â¦ data using several functions (ggplot2, dplyr, tidyr, readr, purrr, â¦) use R version > 3.5 https://www.tidyverse.org/

  2. lubridate: Fast and userfriendly parsing of date-time data, useful for extraction and updating of components of a date-time value. https://www.rdocumentation.org/packages/lubridate/versions/1.7.4

  3. pca3d: This library allows us plotting PCA analysis over data.

install.packages("Rtools") # this package is required for building packages

install.packages("pca3d")# This library is used for PCA analysis

Fetch datasets with R

In this section we explain how to load data from different sources and initially manipulate it to achieve the target frames with all required features, this data is going to be used in the further sections, the notebook is divided in four main experiments : A(News dataset), B(Twitter), C(Movies Reviews) and D(Amazon Reviews). News dataset consists on 20.000 documents divided by folders into several categories, in this example we are going to learn how to fetch data from folders that contains raw (.txt) files. Twitter in a famous social platform where people posts comments and interact with each other, in this case we are going to retrieve #mamba tweets to generate a dataset. Movies reviews (IMDB) is another database that contains already processed files, the target is been binarized and the Bag of Words function is been applied over the texts to extract normalized numerical features. Finally Amazon Reviews dataset consists on a database with reviews and sentiments without any preprocess (similar to IMDB)

In the current experiment we are working with News dataset that can be downloaded in the following link: http://qwone.com/~jason/20Newsgroups/ , first of all we set the path to the dataset folder and load the data for the next steps with âsetwdâ, then we are going to select and fetch every folder we desire (in this case electronics and religion news), and finally we are going to merge data into a unique data Frame.

Preprocessing with R

In this section we are going to learn how to apply the required preprocessing steps for texts, this is called NLP, and in this case we are going to use the libraries âtmâ and âSnowballCâ for Vcorpus and raw lists structures (Experiments A and B), and some features of the library âh2oâ for the previous data Frames.

Experiment A

In this case we are going to apply âtmâ preprocess pipeline to remove the numbers, remove punctuation, transform to lowercase, remove stop words (most frequent and irrelevant as determiners), quit the formatting, stem the words (keep only words root) and finally generate a document tern matrix with every preprocessed terns.

library(tm)
sci.rel
<<VCorpus>>
Metadata:  corpus specific: 0, document level (indexed): 0
Content:  documents: 968
sci.rel.trans=tm_map(sci.rel,removeNumbers)
sci.rel.trans=tm_map(sci.rel.trans,removePunctuation)
sci.rel.trans=tm_map(sci.rel.trans, content_transformer(tolower)) # convert to lowercase
sci.rel.trans=tm_map(sci.rel.trans,removeWords,stopwords("english"))
sci.rel.trans=tm_map(sci.rel.trans,stripWhitespace)

library(SnowballC) # to access Porter's word stemming algorithm
sci.rel.trans=tm_map(sci.rel.trans,stemDocument)

As we can see in the previous chunk, the resultant document tern matrix should be reduce for removing the sparse terns, this helps on overall improving the data quality. Finally we generate a matrix structure disposed for supervised machine learning purposes. That matrix reflects the LM of each sentence as hot vectors (only determining word counts). Finally we assign the last column as types (where we added the categories âscienceâ or âreligionâ).

Experiment D

In this case we are going to preprocess the Amazon reviews datasets, in a similar mode to previous movies reviws, instead of Bag of Words, here we are applying word2vec https://medium.com/@gruizdevilla/introducci%C3%B3n-a-word2vec-skip-gram-model-4800f72c871f to generate the word embeddings, first of all we need to tokenize every clean word.

# Tokenize words
# Set stop words
STOP_WORDS <- read.csv("https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/h2o-tutorials/data/topics/nlp/amazon_reviews/stopwords.csv", stringsAsFactors = FALSE)$STOP_WORD
# Create a tokenize function that tokenizes the sentences and filters certain words
tokenize <- function(sentences, stop_word = STOP_WORDS){
  # Tokenize sentences by word
  tokenized <- h2o.tokenize(sentences, "\\\\W+")
  # Convert words to lowercase
  tokenized_lower <- h2o.tolower(tokenized)
  # Remove words with one letter
  tokenized_filter <- tokenized_lower[(h2o.nchar(tokenized_lower) >= 2) | is.na(tokenized_lower), ]
  # Remove words with any numbers
  tokenized_words <- tokenized_filter[h2o.grep(pattern = "[0-9]", x = tokenized_filter,invert = TRUE, output.logical = TRUE), ]
  # Remove stop words
  tokenized_words <- tokenized_words[is.na(tokenized_words) | !(tokenized_words %in% STOP_WORDS), ]
  return(tokenized_words)
}
# Run the previous tokenization function from the reviews' text
words <- tokenize(reviews$Text)
head(words)

Once we have cleaned all the data, we generate our LM based on word2vec, those models have a powerfull analogy ability, as we can see the retrieval of synonyms is allowed due the nearest words are retrieved on the word embedding space, with the trained lettle model we transform the given data.

# Train a Word2Vec model of 10 dimensions
# It is a computationally demanding process with respect to the vector size
w2v_model <- h2o.word2vec(training_frame = words, vec_size = 40)

  |                                                                      
  |                                                                |   0%
  |                                                                      
  |======                                                          |  10%
  |                                                                      
  |==========================                                      |  40%
  |                                                                      
  |===================================================             |  80%
  |                                                                      
  |==============================================================  |  96%
  |                                                                      
  |================================================================| 100%
# Play with the learned embedding
h2o.findSynonyms(w2v_model, "coffee", count = 5)
# Trasform original words to vectors by means of the learnt Word2Vec model
review_vecs <- h2o.transform(w2v_model, words, aggregate_method = "AVERAGE")
head(review_vecs)

AS we can see the head words we displayed previously have been converted into the numerical features word2vec model assigned to them, in this case we are not talking in terns of word counts probabilities, semantic, syntactic and lexical features have been codified inside those dense vectors, thatâs the reason of being that expensive to calculate. In normal circustances we should train at least with 100 dimension and over large corpora as could be âwikipediaâ, other alternative is using pre-trained models that we are not currently covering here.

# Calculate indexes for a train-test partition, using the 50th quantile of Time variable
time_split <- h2o.quantile(reviews$Time, prob = 0.5)
reviews$Train <- h2o.ifelse(reviews$Time < time_split, "Yes", "No")
train <- reviews[reviews$Train == "Yes", ]
test <- reviews[reviews$Train == "No", ]
# Add aggregated word embeddings. Append columns
ext_reviews <- h2o.cbind(reviews, review_vecs)
# Split data into training and testing
ext_train <- ext_reviews[ext_reviews$Train == "Yes", ]
dim(ext_train)
[1] 49993    52
ext_test <- ext_reviews[ext_reviews$Train == "No", ]
dim(ext_test)
[1] 50007    52

Supervised learning with R (Experiment A)

In this section we are going to review two popular machine learning algorithms K nearest neighbours(K-NN) https://towardsdatascience.com/machine-learning-basics-with-the-k-nearest-neighbors-algorithm-6a6e71d01761 and support vector machine (SVM) https://rpubs.com/Joaquin_AR/267926 , all the stages are propossed for previous experiment A stages, first we are reviewing the training / test split and evaluation configuration, then we are training + evaluating K-NN and SVM models, finally we propose confusiÃ³n and ROC curve tools usage for further understanding the system performance.

Data split and evaluation configuration

In this case we are generating the training / test split and determining 3cross-fold-validdation as evaluation method. Once we split the data we define the evaluation mode as âctrlâ variable, in this case 3-fold-cross-validation https://towardsdatascience.com/why-and-how-to-cross-validate-a-model-d6424b45261f.

library(caret)

ctrl <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv",repeats=3)

As we can see our training data is composed of 727 examples, and testing data with 241 examples, every instance has 119 features, this means that our vocabulary has 118 words, and in each we determine the appearance word counts, the last column is the type to predict.

K-NN and SVM training + evaluation

In this section we review the training of SVM and K NN models, then we evaluate them https://towardsdatascience.com/20-popular-machine-learning-metrics-part-1-classification-regression-evaluation-metrics-1ca3e282a2ce with Sensitivity specificity and ROC stistics, next section will show up the confusion matrix for the target model, we also run some examples to ddetermine the differences between both models, as every Machine Learning experiment here we test SVM model in front of Baseline K NN model. In that way we aim to determine the better way to approach the current task that consists on learn how to assign category (religion or science) for the given documents.

knnModel3x10cv <- train (type ~ ., data=training,method="knn",trControl=ctrl)

ROC curve

In this case we are training k-NN model and plotting the ROC curve as evaluation metric to insight the performance. Notice that we are tunning the âKâ value defined by âtuneLength = 10â, and with every single evaluation from 3-cress-validation we provide the ROC curve.

Deep Learnig with R

In this case we aim to provide some Deep Learning usage examples using H2o library, as we mentioned before we are applying a simple neural network (Multilayer Perceptron) with 3 hidden layers 10 units each.

Experiment C

Both C and D experiment propose the same deep learning model, and we aim to compare them in performance, Check https://medium.com/inveterate-learner/deep-learning-book-chapter-8-optimization-for-training-deep-models-part-i-20ae75984cb2 to better understand whatâs going on inside the model.

Training deep model (Multilayer perceptron)

In this case we train a deep model to estimate the polarity of movies reviews based on the BAg of words extracted features, this model is the provided âbaselineâ to test the strength of the previously generated word embeddings.

# fixing the predictors and output variable
# fixing three layers of 100 neurons each
modelDL <- h2o.deeplearning(x=2:1166, y=1, training_frame = imdb.train, hidden = c(10,10,10))

Calculate performance

In this section we disscuss how to evaluate the performance of deep learning models using h2o library, in the provided report we provide evry single usefull metric to understand possible gaps on training as overfitting (MSE, RMSE and Logloss), and we also provide comparison metrics to determine the performance (AUC, Gini, F1 â¦).

# calculate model performance. The output, first a confusion matrix and then a
# large set of performance statistics: the maximum value of each metric when
# changing the belonging probability threshold to the positive class (0.5, by default)
performanceDL=h2o.performance(modelDL,imdb.test)

Experiment D

In this case we use the previous features generated with word2vec, but we want to insigth the power of LMs even with low training quality. In this case we train the same Multilayer perceptron as in the previous experiment, then we provide the same performance view to allow comparing both system performance.

Training deep model (Multilayer perceptron) with word embeddings as input

In this case we need to define the input schema of the Amazon Reviews dataset with the generated review vecs. In this case we also add the confusion matrix to allow better estimation of the strength that LM has to represent the problem.

library(h2o)
# Train a deep learning predictive model
# Fix the predictors: 4 original and transformed vector's 10 dimensions
predictors <- c('ProductId', 'UserId', 'HelpfulnessNumerator', 'HelpfulnessDenominator','Time', colnames(review_vecs))

response <- c('PositiveReview')

# Learn the model: any operation will take time. Be careful with parameters' values
# An idea to limit the computation: reduce the number of training samples with previous time_split
# Be patient: once the model is learnt, future usage for prediction is justified
modelDL <- h2o.deeplearning(x=predictors, y=response, training_frame =  ext_train, hidden = c(10,10,10))
